## 1. What this deliberation is

The operator has surfaced a question at Session 044 open. The question is verbatim in `00-assessment.md` §2 of this session's provenance folder. In short:

At Session 043 (Path PSD), the Outsider perspective was filled by a Claude subagent; a separate fifth perspective was Google Gemini. The split between Outsider-as-role and non-Claude-as-lineage — historically fused across 21 consecutive sessions (S005 through S041, verified via mechanical manifest inspection in the assessment §3b) — happened without deliberation, was not flagged in the S043 assessment §5 shape proposal as a departure from precedent, and was ratified by the operator's "Proceed" default token without the implication being visible. The operator has declared a position **not for deliberation** — "A Claude is not an Outsider. Filling the Outsider role from inside the Claude family negates the role's function regardless of how the brief reads. This was an error and should not recur." — and has opened two questions **for deliberation**:

- **Why did this happen?**
- **What mitigations?**

The output shapes the operator will consider: substantive MAD v4 revision (engine-v bump candidate); minor documentary clarification + Convene checklist; new OI; combined treatment with OI-019 (since both concern convene-time discipline); partial rejection if the engine identifies a wrong premise in the operator's framing.

The assessment has identified this session as a substantive-revision candidate requiring multi-perspective deliberation per `multi-agent-deliberation.md` v4 §When Multi-Agent Deliberation Is Required (clauses 2 and 3), with non-Claude participation required per §When Non-Claude Participation Is Required clause 2 (output may substantively revise `multi-agent-deliberation.md`). Closed-state OI-004 means `d023_4` does not fire.

## 2. The question set (Q1/Q2/Q3/Q4/Q6/Q7)

Each perspective is asked to answer all six questions to the extent its role allows. A perspective MAY decline to answer a question if it is outside its role — declining explicitly is acceptable and preferable to answering out-of-role. Q5 is deliberately absent per operator R3 — the number is skipped to preserve provenance of the drop.

- **Q1.** Why did the S043 role/lineage split happen? The operator has named five candidate causes: (1) MAD v4 has no normative requirement that Outsider be non-Claude; (2) Convene activity has no lineage-check at convening time; (3) S043 assessment §5 split the historically-fused roles without naming the split as substantive; (4) operator default-token ratification did not surface the implication; (5) §5.6 reopen-warrant (ii) was treated as discharged on lineage-presence grounds without verifying the Outsider specifically. Treat these as seeds, not an exhaustive set. For each candidate, argue load-bearing vs epiphenomenal and name the evidence. If additional causes exist, surface them. Do not stop at obvious explanations.

- **Q2.** Is the operator's declared position ("Claude is not an Outsider; filling the Outsider role from inside the Claude family negates the role's function") correctly scoped? Does it apply symmetrically to every multi-perspective deliberation, or only to deliberations where non-Claude participation is independently required by MAD v4 triggers, or is there some narrower / broader scope that is actually load-bearing? The operator has committed to the position; perspectives may argue its scope is different than stated (narrower, broader, conditioned-differently) but NOT that the position itself is wrong. "The position is correct at a different scope than the operator stated" is a legitimate output; "Claude as Outsider is defensible" is not — that is exactly what the operator has removed from the deliberation.

- **Q3.** What mitigations are warranted? The operator has named four candidates: (1) increase default-read surface so historical Outsider-lineage pattern is visible at session-open; (2) Convene checklist that names lineage per perspective and blocks Claude-as-Outsider absent explicit override; (3) MAD v4 normative addition that Outsider MUST be non-Claude when non-Claude participation is required; (4) multi-family panel discipline as the new default for substantive deliberations. Treat these as seeds, not an exhaustive set. For each proposal, state: (i) mechanism (concrete: what file / what text / what procedure); (ii) anti-laundering risks (what laundering-surface does it open; what is the retrofit risk per OI-019 §5.12 reopen warrant (b) class of concern); (iii) spec-level vs convention-level codification (minor convention with verification window, vs substantive spec amendment); (iv) engine-v bump class if spec-level; (v) interaction with OI-019 (advance / constrain / conflict / neutral). Mitigation 4 should be considered in light of the operator's operational-constraint disclosure — three-family convening is not operationally available for substantive deliberations at present.

- **Q4.** Should MAD v4 gain a normative clause on Outsider lineage? Candidates: (a) "Outsider MUST be non-Claude when non-Claude participation is required" (scope-conditional); (b) "Outsider MUST be non-Claude in all multi-perspective deliberations" (unconditional); (c) "Convene activity MUST enumerate lineage per perspective and halt if Outsider = Claude without explicit override" (procedural, not stance-level); (d) other formulation. For each candidate, argue whether it is correctly scoped, what it would fail to cover, and whether it creates new surfaces for the problem the operator has identified.

- **[Q5 DROPPED per operator R3]** — the premise (three-family panel as new default) was removed by the operator's operational-constraint disclosure in the ratification response. Number preserved to keep the drop audit-visible.

- **Q6.** Is there a combined treatment with OI-019 ("Path-selection work-channel and warrant-surface diversity") that makes operational sense? Both concern convene-time discipline. Candidates: joint deliberation in a future session; shared reopen warrants across OI-019 and any new OI opened here; bundled spec-revision; or coupling-dilution rejection (keep separate). Argue which.

- **Q7.** Is any part of the operator's framing wrong in a way that partial rejection is warranted? The operator has explicitly offered "partial rejection if engine identifies a wrong premise in my framing" as an output shape. Candidates to examine: (a) the "error" characterisation (was the S043 split an error, or a one-time lapse in robust convention, or a symptom of deeper under-specification?); (b) the five candidate causes (is any of them epiphenomenal or wrongly-identified?); (c) the four candidate mitigations (is any of them addressing the wrong root cause?). If you find a wrong premise, name it specifically and state what correct formulation you propose.

## 3. Reading guidance

All perspectives are expected to read:

